widgets_values: You can use either the original clip vision or the normal comfyui clip vision loader, they are the same model in the end.

Adjust the blocks to swap based on your VRAM, this is a tradeoff between speed and memory usage.

Alternatively there's option to use VRAM management introduced in DiffSynt-Studios. This is usually slower, but saves even more VRAM compared to BlockSwap

fp8_fast seems to cause huge quality degradation

fp_16_fast enables "Full FP16 Accmumulation in FP16 GEMMs" feature available in the very latest pytorch nightly, this is around 20% speed boost. 

Sageattn if you have it installed can be used for almost double inference speed

TeaCache could be considered to be sort of an automated step skipper 

The relative l1 threshold -value determines how aggressive this is, higher values are faster but quality suffers more. Very first steps should NEVER be skipped with this model or it kills the motion. When using the pre-calculated coefficients, the treshold value should be much higher than with the default coefficients.
Enhance-a-video can increase the fidelity of the results, too high values lead to noisy results.
If you have Triton installed, connect this for ~30% speed increase
